  "prompt": "What is a 3-regular planar graph?",
  "response": "A 3-regular planar graph is a graph that satisfies three specific conditions:\n\n1. Regularity: Every vertex in the graph has exactly 3 edges connected to it.\n\n2. Planarity: The graph can be drawn on a plane (or a sphere) without any edges crossing.\n\n3. 3-Regular: The degree of each vertex is 3, meaning each vertex is connected to exactly 3 other vertices.\n\nSome key characteristics of 3-regular planar graphs include:\n- They are cubic graphs\n- They can be embedded in a plane without edge crossings\n- Every vertex has exactly 3 incident edges\n- They are symmetric in their vertex connections\n\nAn example of a simple 3-regular planar graph would be the triangular lattice, where each vertex is connected to its three nearest neighbors in a consistent pattern.",
